The food is less than adequate and is extremely over-priced for what you get. Product is not handled safely and expiration dates are regularly ignored.  On my third night as a shift manager for this company, Tara (the owner) happened to stop in on a night we were closing early due to a winter storm. The two others I was working with at the time were extremely new, and never received any form of training on how to do their jobs. I was expected to get 5 hours worth of work done in 2.5, while serving customers during a regular dinner service. We were also told to keep our labor expenses at a minimum, so closes were always rushed. Some minor details were missed which lead to her belittling me and telling me how poor of a supervisor I was, and how I was going to be on a two week probation because of the circumstances. When I tried to explain the situation, she then tried to put the two other new staff members on a two week probation.  I immediately threatened to quit because I refused to let someone who has no idea how their store operates on a day to day basis tell me that I was a bad employee for doing my best under a time crunch. Her entire attitude changed and she tried to rectify the situation by feigned empathy. When I finished counting the nightly deposit, I went back upstairs to finish the tasks I missed as she requested.  I was told that I was to never sweep our floors and to only use a vacuum (that was missing the attachment to actually pick up debris on the floor) upon patronizingly demonstrating how a vacuum works to me, Tara stuck the dirty running vacuum hose to my cheek to prove to me that it worked.  Save your money and eat somewhere else.

First of all, there are no photos to share, as I don't think it fair for The Java House to show an empty establishment by no fault of their own.  That being said, I would like to comment on the great food and drinks they have to offer.  Our first visit was to get a quick, cold drink on a warm afternoon.  The Mango Hibiscus Iced tea my wife ordered was refreshing and Iowish  Cooler that I purchased was very tasty.  Our son selected the Pink Hawk, which was very good as well.  The drinks were generous for the price we paid.  Our family like The Java House so much that we came back the next morning for breakfast.  I ordered the Spicy Southwest Sandwich, my wife the Caprese Egg Sandwich, and my son the Morning Muscle Sandwich.  All three were great, but I though mine Spicy Southwest could have used a bit more spice.  My wife and I, however, were disappointed with the coffee.  She had the American Gothic 16oz pour over, and I the St. Louis Blues 16oz pour over.  Both of us cannot recall ever having pour over coffees before, and our disappointment may be more over our preferences for making coffee than the coffee itself.  Needless to say, neither my wife or I finished our coffees.  Overall, I would recommend The Java House to anyone in the Iowa City area.  The atmosphere (as it was in this Age of COVID) was inviting and comfortable.  The staff were friendly and helpful.

The downtown Java House location is pretty average. I will admit, I avoid going here. It takes about ten minutes on any given day to get a drink here--which is the same amount it takes Starbucks during a rush. At my last visit to Java House, I waited for my drink for 10 minutes before a barista asked me what drink I was waiting for, since everyone who had ordered after me and before me had gotten their drinks. A ticket had apparently not come through or something--it was never made clear. She seemed irritated, like this situation had happened before. Heirloom Salad Co has faster service than the baristas across the room. I will go to this location if I'm not in a hurry, but I don't go out of my way to go here between classes. I moved away from Iowa City for a year and went back to my hometown. One of the first things I found myself missing was Java House. I'm from Texas originally, where drip coffee hasn't caught on, and Starbucks is still the place to go. Java House has great coffee and comfy couches to study on. Students love it for that, and it's open late. It's also joined to a restaurant in case you need something to eat while studying for hours. JH gets 4 stars out of 5 only because they constantly play the most annoying coffee shop music (soft indie; what it is, the early 2000s?) and it gets distracting sometimes, enough that I've had to leave because I couldn't focus on my papers. If they switched to something inoffensive/unnoticeable like classical, I'd be in there constantly.
